{"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "schema", "document", "Document"], "kwargs": {"metadata": {"producer": "Adobe PDF Library 17.0", "creator": "Adobe InDesign 19.5 (Macintosh)", "creationdate": "2025-06-30T13:23:51+01:00", "moddate": "2025-06-30T13:23:54+01:00", "trapped": "/False", "source": "corpus\\autistic-spectrum-v4.pdf", "total_pages": 47, "page": 20, "page_label": "21"}, "page_content": "21\nSensory invalidation\nSensory invalidation describes when an autistic person\u2019s sensory \nchallenges aren\u2019t taken seriously. It can lead to confusion,  \nemotional outbursts, anxiety and camouflaging. It is important to \nrespect autistic children\u2019s sensory differences and validate their \nfeelings and experiences even when you don\u2019t understand it. Below \nare examples of sensory invalidation.\nSensory validation\nMake sure you acknowledge your child\u2019s sensory challenges and make appropriate \nadaptations where possible. Below is an example of sensory validation.\nOw, it hurts\nDon\u2019t be \nsilly, it \ndoesn\u2019t hurt\nIt\u2019s too loud It\u2019s not \nthat bad\nIt\u2019s too loud\nIt\u2019s too loud \nfor you, let\u2019s \nmove away", "type": "Document"}}